{#-
  Minds variant of the packaged spec-mapper prompt (libs/mngr_tmr's
  spec_mapper.j2). Unlike the docstring-TMR variant (mapper.j2, a
  self-contained fork because its delta was subtractive), this variant is
  purely additive: it extends the packaged template and fills its two
  block slots, so the mapper contract lives in exactly one place. Passed
  via --mapper-prompt by the `tmr-specs-minds` justfile recipe.
-#}
{% extends "spec_mapper.j2" %}

{% block project_guidance %}
You are working on the tests for the minds app (`apps/minds/`), the desktop
client for managing mngr agents. Place each new witnessing test by the
repo's test taxonomy (see style_guide.md):

- Default to an integration test: a `test_*.py` file in the source package
  folder, no pytest mark, no live network. Most spec scenarios (HTTP-level
  authentication flows, redirects, session handling) are drivable this way
  against the app's server with local fixtures.
- Use a unit test (`<module>_test.py` next to the module) only when the
  observable behavior is testable fully in-process (e.g. a pure token
  validation property).
- Use `@pytest.mark.release` when the flow genuinely needs the full stack
  (a real workspace, Docker, a deployed env). Reserve
  `@pytest.mark.acceptance` for core flows; most slow tests belong in
  release.
- Reuse the shared fixtures from the relevant `conftest.py` and helpers
  from `testing.py` files; read them before writing new setup. Match the
  surrounding tests' idioms, and never use unittest.mock or
  monkeypatch.setattr.
{% endblock %}

{% block infra_blockers %}
Minds-specific capability limits to recognize (these are shared blockers,
not things to hack around locally): many minds tests need infrastructure a
single test cannot stand up -- a Docker daemon and a pre-baked workspace
snapshot (`minds_snapshot_resume`), a deployed Modal env (`minds_deployment`
mints its own; `minds_services` needs a shared one), or secrets (an
`ANTHROPIC_API_KEY`, imbue_cloud login, Modal deploy tokens, litellm keys).
If a witnessing test would need such setup and it is absent from THIS
environment, record the blocker instead of faking the behavior.
{% endblock %}
